{{infobox company | name = Pure Indian Foods | logo = File:Pure_Indian_Foods_Logo_RGB_Full_Color.jpg | logo_size = | type = Private | founded = 2008 | founder = Sandeep Agarwal | hq_location = [[Princeton Junction, New Jersey]] | website = {{URL|http://www.pureindianfoods.com/}} }}
'''Pure Indian Foods''' is an organic, grass-fed herbal and spiced [[ghee]] manufacturer and distributor headquartered in [[Princeton Junction, New Jersey]].<ref name=timesofindia>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/Clarified-butter/articleshow/7753149.cms?#|title=Clarified butter|date=March 21, 2011|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=harvesttable>{{cite news|title=Beyond Butter, Discovering Ghee|date=September 2010|publisher=The Harvest Table}}</ref><ref name=coloradosprings/> The company was founded by Sandeep Agarwal and his wife in 2008.<ref name=nytimes/><ref name=njmonthly/><ref name=nypost/>
==History== Pure Indian Foods is based out of Princeton, New Jersey and owned by husband and wife team, Sandeep and Nalini Agarwal. In 1889, Nalini’s family founded a ghee business in northern India.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/21/dining/21ghees.html?_r=0|title=Ghee, Indian-Style Butter, With a Kick|publisher=The New York Times|date=July 10, 2010|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=njmonthly>{{cite web|url=http://njmonthly.com/articles/jersey-living/power-to-the-pantry/|title=Power to the Pantry: Jersey-Made Products Abound|date=March 13, 2013|publisher=New Jersey Monthly|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nypost>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/03/09/ghee-food-product-built-on-an-old-idea/|title=‘Ghee’ food product built on an old idea|publisher=New York Post|date=March 9, 2014|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=theglobeandmail>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/food-and-wine/food-trends/omghee-is-this-clarified-butter-good-or-what/article4439185/|title=OMGhee: Is this clarified butter good or what?|publisher=The Globe and Mail|date=July 24, 2012|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref> In 2008, the Agarwal's established Pure Indian Foods to continue his family business in the United States.<ref name=nytimes/><ref name=njmonthly/><ref name=nypost/> Previously, he worked as an [[information technology|IT]] specialist on Wall Street.<ref name=nypost/><ref name=centraljersey>{{cite news|title=It's like buttah!|date=March 25, 2013|author=Stephaie Vaccaro}}</ref> In 2012, the company began shipping to Canada.<ref name=theglobeandmail/> That October, Pure Indian Foods won two awards at the American Herbalist Guild Symposium.<ref name=centraljersey/> The Whole Earth Center was the first store to carry the company’s ghee.<ref name=centraljersey/> In March 2015, the company created Coffee++, a MCT oil and grass-fed ghee product to make oiled coffee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theboxmag.com/article/fueled-oiled-coffee-9888|title=Fueled by Oiled Coffee|date=March 6, 2015|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref>
==Operations== Pure Indian Foods is based in [[Princeton Junction, New Jersey]].<ref name=nytimes/> The company uses cream from free-ranging dairy herds in New Jersey for their products.<ref name=coloradosprings>{{cite news|title=ON FOOD: Area shop, website sell great ghee, oil, vinegar|date=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=nytimes/><ref name=theglobeandmail/> Additionally, Pure Indian Foods uses non-homogenized milk in the spring and fall when grass grows rapidly to give its products a high amount of fat-soluble vitamins and [[Conjugated Linoleic Acid|Conjugated Linoleic Acid (CLA)]].<ref name=paleomagonline>{{cite web|url=http://paleomagonline.com/review-pure-indian-foods/|title=Review: Pure Indian Foods|date=January 5, 2014|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref> Pure Indian Foods produces ghee, butter with the milk solids and water removed, in multiple variations including digestive, garlic, herbes de provence, Indian dessert, Italian and Niter Kebbeh.<ref name=theglobeandmail/><ref name=paleomagonline/>
==References== {{Reflist}}
